[The report above includes a new piece of information, the suggestion that the BTV-14 strain in question is probably a vaccine strain. It will be interesting to obtain science-based data on the issue.

Subscribers may recall that in late 2008, BTV-6 (Germany and Netherlands) and BTV-11 (Belgium), which were found to have circulated in cattle, without clinical disease, were in fact closely related to South African vaccine strains. For details, see ProMED-mail posting 20090304.0888.

Russia's initial OIE report on BTV-14, submitted 30 Dec 2011, mentioned positive serology (ELISA and CFT) in cattle, sheep, and goats, serotyping pending, without clinical disease. Follow-up report no 1, submitted 14 Mar 2012, mentioned virus isolation and serotyping as BTV-14. No clinical disease has been reported. Further data have been reviewed in (commentary) to posting 20121123.1422112.

Information on Russia's own BT situation is rather scarce.

Bluetongue disease was 1st registered in Russia in July 1993 on the territory of the Buryat Republic, diagnosed by the All-Russian Scientific-Research Institute for Veterinary Virology and Microbiology, Pokrov (Vladimir oblast). Testing of organ or blood samples taken from sheep by solid phase (SF) ELISA using monoclonal antibodies (MA) revealed presence of bluetongue virus antigen. Then, the virus was isolated in Siberian ibex kidney (SIK) cell culture and newborn mice, identified by using SF ELISA and fluorescent antibody (FA) methods and compliment fixation test (CFT). Typing made by neutralization test (NT) showed it belonged to the BTV-16 serotype. (Ref 1).

A serological survey in Kazakhstan, 1997-1998, showed seroprevalence for BT virus in cattle, sheep, and goats. Seropositive animals were found to be widespread, suggesting endemicity. No serotyping has become available (Ref 2).

Details on other scientific papers on BTV in Russia will be appreciated, if available.

Some questions come to mind:
- Have sero-surveys in local ruminants been conducted on Russian territories since 2000?
- Have there been additional clinically suspected cases in sheep, the species known to be most susceptible to BTV, after 1993?
- Have samples been submitted for laboratory investigations from such cases? Could figures/locations/results become available?

A map of the Russian Federation (Buryt Republic - navy blue; Kazakhstan - light brown) is available at http://tinyurl.com/cgg987p.

References
----------
1. IF Vishnyakov, AA Strizhakov, MB Novikova, AV Lunitzyn, et al: Identification and typing of virus bluetongue. Veterinariya (Moscow). 1995, 4, 20-5. (Russian, English abstract; thanks to Faina Golander and Efrat Havusha, Library, Kimron Veterinary Institute, for their excellent assistance).
2. M Lundervold, EJ Milner-Gulland, CJ O'Callaghan, and C Hamblin: First evidence of bluetongue virus in Kazakhstan. Vet Microbiology. 2003; 92(3): 281-7. - Mod.AS]
